<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910201-0143</DOCNO><DOCID>910201-0143.</DOCID><HL>   SCEcorp Is Named   In Unusual Trust Suit   By California Energy</HL><DATE>02/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CE SCE GE SDO</CO><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)SECURITIES (SCR)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   SAN FRANCISCO -- California Energy Co., a geothermalenergy concern, filed an unusual $780 million antitrust suit,alleging that defendants including its biggest customer,SCEcorp, tried to drive it out of business.   The suit, filed yesterday in federal court here, alleges awidespread pattern by SCEcorp to monopolize theelectric-generating business in Southern California, and todiscourage development of alternative energy sources. Amongother things, the complaint alleges that SCEcorp executivesillegally pressured California Energy's principal lenders tocut off credit to the company and also engaged in a campaignof &quot;commercial disparagement&quot; against it. SCEcorp is theparent of Southern California Edison Co.</LP><TEXT>   Also named as a defendant was General Electric Co.'sKidder, Peabody andamp; Co. investment firm unit, which accordingto allegations in the complaint, conducted &quot;unlawful bearraids on plaintiff's shares,&quot; designed to drive down theprice of California Energy shares.   &quot;Southern California Edison with its fossil fuel plantshas tried to stunt our growth because of our aggressivecompetition,&quot; California Energy said in a statement. SouthernCalifornia Edison also is California Energy's largest buyerof power under long-term sales contracts.   The suit seeks $260 million in damages and asks thatdamages be tripled to $780 million in accordance withapplicable law. It also seeks an injunction barring thepending merger between Southern California Edison and SanDiego Gas andamp; Electric Co. on grounds that it would create anunlawful monopoly. As reported, California public utilityofficials were expected to issue a preliminary decision onthe $2.56 billion acquisition today.   In Rosemead, Calif., a spokeswoman for SCEcorp, &quot;We havenot seen the suit yet. It was a surprise to us. But we feelpretty confident that it is going to be a suit without merit,and we are certainly going to defend ourselves vigorously.&quot;   In New York, a spokeswoman for Kidder Peabody said thefirm was declining to comment on the suit because it alsohadn't seen it.</TEXT></DOC>